title: Add random uuid support for streamlit
body:
This PR adds support for random uuid in streamlit dashboard.

A lot of times, there seem to be duplicate widget keys which cause streamlit errors (for example: #205). This PR makes it so that the keys are generated randomly and have a very low chance of collision. Essentially, all streamlit calls that require a key parameter have been wrapped with a `random_uuid_wrapper` that persists the randomly generated keys throught the session.

title: Add test for visuals dimensionality reduction
body:
This PR adds tests for visuals dimensionality reduction i.e. it tests if UMAP and TSNE visualizations are created correctly for both 2D and 3D dimension.

There's also added support for `dashboard_name` parameter in order to prevent file overwrite when using two or more UMAP/TSNE visuals.

The result of the test looks as follows:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/72266394/230780993-c06bc8fd-a7c4-4286-b9bc-eddd144874e7.png)

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/72266394/230781022-d0aa9c73-eab8-4ee8-9f5f-531a7b73f2d2.png)

However, there's a streamlit error when trying to view both of UMAP or both of TSNE on the dashboard (like in the test). This is because of the colliding `plot_name` key for streamlit checkbox that is internally set to `self.visual_type` (either "UMAP" or "t_SNE")  when two or more of the same type visuals are present. I believe the fix is slightly hard here since st_run.py has "UMAP" and "t_SNE" filenames hardcoded for plotting.

Let's brainstorm the easiest way to fix this.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/72266394/230781196-f5184ff0-90cc-4139-bbfc-322164eaa0e8.png)

Proposal for implementing a style guide in the framework and examples
body:
Currently, it isn't enforced to follow a style guide (such as pep8) when working on the framework or examples. This could lead to inconsistent formatting across files as different contributors get involved. I propose using an automated code formatter tool that will make it easy for new contributors to format their code as expected in the style-guide as well as format current non-style-guide compliant code.

After looking at multiple other open-source repositories, the leading automated code formatter seems to be [Black](https://github.com/psf/black). Projects also usually add it to their DevOps pipeline to automate the process on every new code contribution.

Black has very simple usage:

```
# run as script
black {source_file_or_directory}

# or run as package
python3 -m black {source_file_or_directory}
```

To encourage new contributors to adhere to the style-guide, I propose adding instructions to run Black in the [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/uptrain-ai/uptrain/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md) file. Furthermore, the tool can be used to format the existing code base to ensure consistency in the formatting.

Overall, integrating Black into the UpTrain framework and examples would improve the consistency and readability of the codebase, while simplifying the code formatting process for all contributors.

title: Add a concept drift algorithm for regression tasks
body:
Concept drift is the measure of model performance degradation. For binary classification, we use the [DDM algorithm](https://github.com/uptrain-ai/uptrain/blob/main/uptrain/core/classes/algorithms/data_drift_ddm.py). We want to implement a concept drift detection algorithm for regression tasks as well.

The concept drift algorithm will go inside [this if-else condition](https://github.com/uptrain-ai/uptrain/blob/main/uptrain/core/classes/monitors/concept_drift.py#L23) in `concept_drift.py`.

[ADWIN](https://riverml.xyz/dev/api/drift/ADWIN/) is a good algorithm to get started (but feel free to implement your own).

title: Measure Accuracy for Regression Models
body:
In regression models, the output is continuous. We want to add a measure to track the loss in such cases. One popular metric is [Mean Absolute Error (MAE)](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/model_evaluation.html#mean-absolute-error).

We want to implement this to track accuracy for regression models as a part of the UpTrain package. See [ride time estimation](https://github.com/uptrain-ai/uptrain/blob/main/examples/ride_time_estimation/run.ipynb) for example of a regression problem.

One way to do that would be to add another measureable (called MAEMeasurable) inside the [accuracy measurable file](https://github.com/uptrain-ai/uptrain/blob/main/uptrain/core/classes/measurables/accuracy.py).

Also, a good first issue to get started with UpTrain.
